game 15 move 9: 
game 15 move 10: Tartakower: Less consistent than 6.a3 or 6.Bd3, maintaining as long as possible the tension in the center.
game 15 move 11: 
game 15 move 12: 
game 15 move 13: 
game 15 move 14: 
game 15 move 15: 
game 15 move 16: 
game 15 move 17: 
game 15 move 18: ? Schlechter: A very bad place for the queen. The best continuation is 10.cxd5 exd5 11.Be2, followed by O-O. *** Tartakower: Loss of time. The queen will soon have to seek a better square (14.Qe2). The most useful move is 10.Qc2.
game 15 move 19: ! Schlechter: A fine sacrifice of a pawn. If 11.cxd5 exd5 12.Nxd5? Nxd5 13.Qxd5 Rd8! and Black has a strong attack.
game 15 move 20: Schlechter: Better was 11.cxd5 exd5 12.Be2.
game 15 move 21: 
game 15 move 22: 
game 15 move 23: 
game 15 move 24: 
game 15 move 25: 
game 15 move 26: 
game 15 move 27: 
game 15 move 28: 
game 15 move 29: ! Schlechter: Introduced by Marshall and Schlechter in a similar position with opposite colors, but here with the extra move Rd8.
game 15 move 30: 
game 15 move 31: Tartakower: Threatening to win a pawn by 17...Bxh2+ 18.Kxh2 Qd6+. White's next move provides against this, but loosens the kingside defenses.
game 15 move 32: 
game 15 move 33: 
game 15 move 34: 
game 15 move 35: 
game 15 move 36: 
game 15 move 37: 
game 15 move 38: 
game 15 move 39: !
game 15 move 40: Schlechter: There is no defense; e.g., 21.Bxh7+ Kxh7 22.Qxg4 Rd2 etc.; or 21.h3 Qh4 22.Qxg4 Qxg4 23.hxg4 Rxd3, threatening ...Rh3 mate and ...Rxc3; or 21.Qxg4 Rxd3 22.Ne2 Rc2 23.Bc1 g6! threatening ...h5; or 21.Ne4 Qh4 22.h3 (if 22.g3 Qxh2+ 23.Qxh2 Nxh2 and wins.) 22....Rxd3 23.Qxd3 Bxe4 24.Qxe4 Qg3 25.hxg4 Qh4+ mate.
game 15 move 41: 
game 15 move 42: Schlechter: Or 22.h3 Rxc3! 23.Bxc3 Bxe4 24.Qxg4 Qxg4 25.hxg4 Rd3 wins. *** Tartakower: The alternative 22.h3, parrying the mate, would lead to the following brilliant lines of play: 22...Rxc3! (an eliminating sacrifice, getting rid of the knight, which overprotects the bishop on e4) 23.Bxc3 (or 23.Qxg4 Rxh3+ 24.Qxh3 Qxh3+ 25.gxh3 Bxe4+ 26.Kh2 Rd2+ 27.Kg3 Rg2+ 28.Kh4 Bd8+ 29.Kh5 Bg6+ mate) 23...Bxe4+ 24.Qxg4 (if 24.Qxe4 Qg3 25.hxg4 Qh4+ mate) 24...Qxg4 25.hxg4 Rd3 with the double threat of 26...Rh3+ mate and 26....Rxc3, and Black wins. Beautiful as are these variations, the continuation in the text is still more splendid.
