game 16 move 153: -8.11/24 5.0s, White wins by adjudication
game 17 pre-move: Last but not least, let's take a look at a famous and celebrated game that Tal played in his later years. It was played in Reykjavik in 1987 and Tal's opponent was well-known Icelandic grandmaster Johann Hjartarson.
game 17 move 0: Back to old loves in the old age?
game 17 move 1: 
game 17 move 2: 
game 17 move 3: 
game 17 move 4: As Kasparov wrote somewhere - "The ability to handle different structures that result from the Ruy Lopez is what determins the class of a certain player". It is no wonder most World Champions played the Ruy with at least one colour - and Tal was no exception.
game 17 move 5: 
game 17 move 6: 
game 17 move 7: 
game 17 move 8: 
game 17 move 9: 
game 17 move 10: 
game 17 move 11: 
game 17 move 12: 
game 17 move 13: 
game 17 move 14: 
game 17 move 15: 
game 17 move 16: 
game 17 move 17: The Chigorin variation of the Closed Ruy Lopez is one of the oldest systems at Black's disposal in this complex opening that has been played on all levels for more than 100 years. These days, it is not the most frequent guest at the highest level as there are other, more reliable systems available to Black, but for average patzers like you and me, there is a very high probability we are going to encounter it sooner or later if we play 1.e4, 2.Nf3, 3.Bb5 and 4. Ba4.
game 17 move 18: 
game 17 move 19: 
game 17 move 20: 
game 17 move 21: 
game 17 move 22: This is the old way of handling this variation.
game 17 move 23: One of the numerous possibilities at Black's disposal in this system.
game 17 move 24: 
game 17 move 25: 
game 17 move 26: 
game 17 move 27: 
game 17 move 28: [%cal Ge3c4,Ge3f5,Ge3d5,Ge3c2] The knight is very agile on e3, covering the important c4 square, defending the bishop on c2 and potentially eyeing the d5 and f5 squares.
game 17 move 29: A typical Chigorin maneuver. The knight puts pressure on the d4 pawn and intends to go to b4 after White closes the center, in order to harass the bishop on c2.
game 17 move 30: 
game 17 move 31: 
game 17 move 32: 
game 17 move 33: [%csl Gc5][%cal Gb4a6,Gb5b4,Ga6c5] One of the ideas behind Black's setup is this queenside expansion. They want to get the moves a5-b4 and then securely land the knight on c5.
game 17 move 34: 
game 17 move 35: 
game 17 move 36: A very nice tactical way of preventing Black from executing this plan. Remember this idea of playing b4 in this type of structure as it happens very often in the Ruy.
game 17 move 37: This move is a common idea in different Ruy Lopez structures. Sometimes, it leads to the fianchetto of the bishop via f8-g7 route, but sometimes the knight can also appear on this square.
game 17 move 38: Now White obtains a very typical advantage in this type of variation because he has a big space advantage and the knight on a6 is completely out of the game. However, Black's position is very sturdy and solid and it takes a great player to outmaneuver and outplay Black from a position as this.
game 17 move 39: White was potentially threatening to take on a5, so Black avoids this option, even though it does open the a-file.
game 17 move 40: 
game 17 move 41: 
game 17 move 42: [%csl Rb5] Another feature of this position is the weakness of the b5 pawn which White can utilize when maneuvering the pieces.
game 17 move 43: [%csl Gb5][%cal Gc7b5,Gc7e8,Ge8g7] Adding some protection to the b5 square and maybe - just maybe - hinting at the potential Ne8-Ng7 route?
game 17 move 44: The knight on e3 has finally done its job and now it moves out of the way to free the bishop on d2 to seek a more promising role.
game 17 move 45: [%cal Gh5f4,Gf7f5] Black has to create counterplay on the kingside - either with the Nf4 knight jump or with the f5 pawn push.
game 17 move 46: White decides to ignore it and threaten Ra7 for now, although it is not 100% clear whether the bishop is better placed on e3 or d2 (given that on e3 it can be hit with the f-pawn). There are other alternatives, but the character of the position remains the same nevertheless.
game 17 move 47: 
game 17 move 48: 
game 17 move 49: It is logical for Black to try and exchange some pieces when they have less space.
game 17 move 50: An unconventional decision (how many of us would automatically recapture with the rook)? But White wants to bring the knight to b3 square and then potentially eye the a5 or even the c5 square (spoiler alert) .
game 17 move 51: [%cal Gf5f4] Finally Black initiaties counterplay at the moment when our queen is locking the bishop and when f4 is actually a threat.
game 17 move 52: [%cal Rh6f8] Placing the bishop outside of the chain and avoiding the threat.
game 17 move 53: But this move is actually very passive and totally misguided. The knight was very decent on h5 and it was absolutely not necessary to move it. Hjartarson was maybe considering a kingside attack with f4 and so on, but this is a wrong idea in this position.
game 17 move 54: 
game 17 move 55: Closing down the position, in my opinion, only helps White as now the counterplay on the kingside is not happening any time soon and it is unrealistic to expect any sort of King's Indian pawn storm with g5-g4 given the current positioning of the pieces.
game 17 move 56: 
game 17 move 57: 
game 17 move 58: 
game 17 move 59: 
game 17 move 60: [%csl Rc6] White treis to increase the pressure on the queenside and bring the pieces closer. The c6 square is looking quite juicy.
game 17 move 61: 
game 17 move 62: 
game 17 move 63: 
game 17 move 64: 
game 17 move 65: Now the knight arrives back - but where is it going now that the f4 square has been covered?
game 17 move 66: 
game 17 move 67: Maybe Hjartarson was hoping to get the pawn chain going with g5-g4 and so on, but it is way too slow.
game 17 move 68: 
game 17 move 69: The culminating moment of this entire game!
game 17 move 70: A wonderful move, that is not only spectacular, but also very strong! The idea is very simple - either the pawn on b5 falls - or the pawn on d6 is diverted from the defence of the e5 pawn. One of those rare cases where Tal's sacrifice was very positionally founded - and very correct :).
game 17 move 71: 
game 17 move 72: And now the pawn falls and White obtains a strong passed b-pawn.
game 17 move 73: A final mistake in a lost position.
game 17 move 74: [%cal Rd3a6] Now White simplifies into a much more winning endgame with the help of another very spectacular sacrifice. First, a simple discovered attack on the queen.
game 17 move 75: 
game 17 move 76: A tremendous blow at the most fortified point - once again utilizing the weakness of the dark-squares around the black king.
game 17 move 77: 
game 17 move 78: 
game 17 move 79: Threatening mate on the spot and at least forcing accuraccy to the very end.
game 17 move 80: 
game 17 move 81: 
game 17 move 82: 
game 17 move 83: 
game 17 move 84: And here Hjartarson resigned not waiting for
game 17 move 85: 
game 17 move 86: Although he might have as well allowed mate here to honor Tal's brilliant play. A fascinating game and one of the rare examples where Tal's combinations had a strictly positional foundation. --- On the other hand, apart from the splendid combination, I also found Tal's handling of a typical Spanish middlegame extremely instructive. We often admire his combinations and tend to forget he was also a very well-rounded player with above average positional understanding.
